{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}} {{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}} {{Infobox football biography | name = Ethan Ampadu | image = Ethan Ampadu 2017.jpg | image_size = | caption = Ampadu playing for Chelsea U23s in 2017 | fullname = Ethan Kwame Colm Raymond Ampadu<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thefa.com/-/media/files/thefaportal/governance-docs/registrations/july-2017.ashx|title=List of Players Registered as Scholars in Accordance with Rule C.3 Between 01/07/2017 and 31/07/2017|accessdate=26 September 2017|format=PDF|page=46|publisher=The FA}}</ref> | birth_date = {{birth date and age|2000|9|14|df=y}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/players/19731/Ethan-Ampadu/overview |title=Ethan Ampadu: Overview |publisher=Premier League |accessdate=5 October 2018}}</ref> | birth_place = [[Exeter]], England | height = {{convert|1.82|m|order=flip}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.chelseafc.com/en/teams/first-team/ethan-ampadu?pageTab=biography |title=Ethan Ampadu |publisher=Chelsea F.C. |accessdate=5 October 2018}}</ref> | position = [[Centre back]] / [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|Defensive midfielder]] | currentclub = [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] | clubnumber = 44 | youthyears1 = 2008–2016 | youthclubs1 = [[Exeter City F.C.|Exeter City]] | years1 = 2016–2017 | clubs1 = [[Exeter City F.C.|Exeter City]] | caps1 = 8 | goals1 = 0 | years2 = 2017– | clubs2 = [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] | caps2 = 1 | goals2 = 0 | nationalyears1 = 2015 | nationalteam1 = [[England national under-16 football team|England U16]] | nationalcaps1 = 1 | nationalgoals1 = 0 | nationalyears2 = 2016 | nationalteam2 = [[Wales national under-17 football team|Wales U17]] | nationalcaps2 = 5 | nationalgoals2 = 0 | nationalyears3 = 2016– | nationalteam3 = [[Wales national under-19 football team|Wales U19]] | nationalcaps3 = 3 | nationalgoals3 = 0 | nationalyears4 = 2017– | nationalteam4 = [[Wales national football team|Wales]] | nationalcaps4 = 6 | nationalgoals4 = 0 | club-update = 22:28, 12 December 2017 (UTC) | nationalteam-update = 22:23, 16 November 2018 (UTC) }} '''Ethan Kwame Colm Raymond Ampadu''' (born 14 September 2000) is a professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[centre back]] or [[defensive midfielder]] for {{English football updater|Chelsea}} club [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] and the [[Wales national football team|Welsh national team]]. He made his senior debut for Wales in November 2017. Ampadu previously played for [[Exeter City F.C.|Exeter City]], where he became the youngest player to appear for the club's first team, aged 15.
==Club career== ===Exeter City=== Born in [[Exeter]], [[Devon]], Ampadu is the son of former professional footballer [[Kwame Ampadu]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36949680 |title=Exeter City 1–0 Brentford |publisher=BBC Sport |date=9 August 2016 |accessdate=10 August 2016}}</ref> A product of the [[Exeter City F. C.|Exeter City]] youth academy, making an appearance for the under-18 squad at the age of 14,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/chelsea-teenager-ethan-ampadu-set-11519170 |title=Chelsea teenager Ethan Ampadu to be handed first Wales start – just a year after Exeter bow at 15|publisher=''Daily Mirror'' |date=14 November 2017|accessdate=11 September 2018}}</ref> he made his senior debut—aged 15 years 10 months and 26 days—in an [[EFL Cup]] first round match against [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] at [[St James Park (Exeter)|St James Park]] on 9 August 2016, playing the full 120 minutes of a 1–0 victory.<ref>{{cite news|title=Exeter City 1–0 On , Brentford|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36949680|accessdate=11 November 2017|publisher=BBC Sport|date=9 August 2016}}</ref> He became the club's youngest ever player, breaking an 87-year-old record set by [[Cliff Bastin]], and being named man of the match.<ref>{{cite twitter|user=officialecfc|number=763123448759590916|title=15-year-old Ethan Ampadu wins the man-of-the-match award on his full debut for the club. Well done, Ethan!|date=9 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.exeterexpressandecho.co.uk/exeter-city-vs-brentford-ethan-ampadu-to-become-exeter-city-s-youngest-ever-player/story-29602487-detail/story.html|title=Exeter City vs Brentford: Ethan Ampadu to become Exeter City's youngest ever player|date=9 August 2016|publisher=''ExeterExpressandEcho.co.uk''|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160810163205/http://www.exeterexpressandecho.co.uk/exeter-city-vs-brentford-ethan-ampadu-to-become-exeter-city-s-youngest-ever-player/story-29602487-detail/story.html|archivedate=10 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/who-ethan-ampadu-wales-face-11729005|title=The 15-year-old wonderkid England want to poach has just become big news|first=Paul|last=Abbandonato|date=10 August 2016|publisher=''Wales Online''}}</ref> A week later, he made his league debut in a 1–0 home defeat against [[Crawley Town F.C.|Crawley Town]] in [[EFL League Two]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Exeter City 0–1 Crawley Town|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/37018095|accessdate=11 November 2017|publisher=BBC Sport|date=16 August 2016}}</ref>
===Chelsea=== On 1 July 2017, Ampadu signed a contract with [[Premier League]] club [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]. The two clubs had entered negotiations over a compensation fee for the player in an attempt to reach a fee that both found acceptable for the then 16-year-old. Yet, in November 2017, [[Exeter City F.C.|Exeter City]] chairman Julian Tagg said that, whilst there was still a positive relationship between the two clubs, there was also a "massive disparity" in both clubs' valuation of the player. It was set to go to a tribunal.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.devonlive.com/sport/football/football-news/what-know-far-chelsea-exeter-781193|title=What we know so far about the Ethan Ampadu tribunal|last=Byrom|first=David|date=15 November 2017|work=devonlive|accessdate=6 January 2018}}</ref>
On 20 September 2017, Ampadu made his debut for Chelsea in an EFL Cup third round match against [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]], coming on in the 55th minute for [[Cesc Fàbregas]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/41249727|title=Chelsea 5–1 Nottingham Forest|publisher=BBC Sport|date=20 September 2017|accessdate=20 September 2017}}</ref> Doing so made him the first player born in the 2000s to play for the Chelsea senior team. At 17 years and six days old, he also became the youngest player to debut for the club in over ten years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/ethan-ampadu-becomes-youngest-chelsea-player-in-over-a/bc21v7w4akx81wegeigdlwkge |title=Ethan Ampadu becomes youngest Chelsea player in over a decade |date=20 September 2017 |publisher=Goal}}</ref> On 12 December 2017, he made his Premier League debut for Chelsea, coming on as a substitute against [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]] in the 80th minute.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42232614|title=Huddersfield Town 1–3 Chelsea|publisher=BBC Sport|date=12 December 2017|accessdate=21 December 2017}}</ref>
==International career== Ampadu plays internationally for the [[Wales national football team]]. He qualifies for Wales through his Welsh mother.<ref>[https://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/who-ethan-ampadu-wales-face-11729005 Ampadu Welsh qualified]</ref> He was previously also eligible to represent England, Republic of Ireland and Ghana.<ref name="walesonline">{{cite web|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/manchester-united-fc-target-ethan-11154499|title=Why Man Utd target Ethan Ampadu chose Wales over England|first=Gareth|last=Rogers|date=7 April 2016|work=WalesOnline.co.uk}}</ref>
On 26 May 2017, at the age of 16, Ampadu was called into the [[Wales national football team|senior Wales squad]] ahead of their World Cup qualifier with [[Serbia national football team|Serbia]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Ethan Ampadu: Exeter City youngster included in Wales squad|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40041499|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|accessdate=26 May 2017}}</ref> He was called up again on 1 November for friendlies against [[France national football team|France]] and [[Panama national football team|Panama]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Byrom|first1=David|title=Chelsea starlet Ethan Ampadu included in Wales squad for November friendlies|url=http://www.devonlive.com/sport/football/football-news/chelsea-starlet-ethan-ampadu-included-712273|accessdate=11 November 2017|publisher=Devon Live|date=1 November 2017}}</ref> and made his debut on 10 November at the [[Stade de France]], coming on as a 63rd-minute substitute for [[Joe Ledley]] in a 2–0 defeat to the French.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41854507 |title=France 2–0 Wales |publisher=BBC Sport |date=10 November 2017 |accessdate=11 November 2017}}</ref>
